import Mathlib

open Filter Set

/- A norm on a vector space is called a Lorentz norm if it is of the form
  ‖x‖_p = ( ∑ x_i ^ p ) ^ (1/p), where p ≥ 1.
  A norm on a vector space is called an Orlicz norm if it is of the form
  ‖x‖_φ = inf { λ > 0 | ∑ φ(x_i / λ) ≤ 1 }, where φ is a convex function
  such that φ(0) = 0 and φ(x) ≥ 0 for all x.
  The proof of the following theorem is missing.
  A theorem by J. L. Doob (1961) states that for a discrete time Markov chain,
  the transition probabilities satisfy the Lorentz norm condition if and only
  if they satisfy the Orlicz norm condition with a specific convex function.
  The proof of this theorem is quite involved and requires several lemmas about
  the properties of Lorentz and Orlicz norms.  -/
theorem RCLike.norm_I {K : Type u_1} [RCLike K] : ‖(RCLike.I : K)‖ = if RCLike.I ≠ (0 : K) then 1 else 0 := by
  split_ifs with h
  · apply RCLike.norm_I_of_ne_zero h
  · push_neg at h
    simpa

